<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Buildings: Getting Started
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Introduction to buildings, building types, and automatic features.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What are Buildings and Facets?
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Buildings tab</Bold> houses all the facets (walls, doors, ladders, cables,
        fences, gates) used in your map. In Urban Chaos, <Bold>buildings</Bold> are containers
        that organize related <Bold>facets</Bold> together.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        All facets must be attached to at least one building, but not all buildings need to form
        closed rectangular structures. Buildings are simply organizational containers — you can
        have standalone fences, cables, or walls all attached to a "building" even if they don't
        form a physical structure.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Buildings tab showing the Buildings list, Facets list, and Polygons column
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,16,0,4">
        Building Types
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When creating a new building, you must choose between two types. This choice affects
        how the building's interior is rendered and how doors function.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        House
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Houses</Bold> are decorative buildings with no interior sections for the player
        to walk inside. The player can climb on rooftops and exterior surfaces, but cannot
        enter the structure. If you place a door on a house building, it functions as an
        <Bold>elevator</Bold> — teleporting the player directly to the top of the building.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Houses use the standard PAP (PAP) rendering system where the
        cell altitude determines the roof height, and roof textures are automatically applied
        when a closed polygon is detected.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Warehouse
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Warehouses</Bold> are designed to contain playable interior areas. Players can
        enter through doors and walk around inside. Warehouses use a distinct rendering mechanism:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The <Bold>PAP cell altitude remains at 0</Bold> (ground level) — it does not
                change to represent the roof height.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Roof tiles (RF4 entries)</Bold> define the walkable height inside the warehouse,
                matching the interior footprint of the closed polygon.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Floor textures</Bold> are applied automatically to the interior instead of
                roof textures (specifically <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">tex287hi</Run>
                from the Shared texture group).
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Only the <Bold>PAP Hidden flag</Bold> is set on interior tiles, signaling that
                the PAP layer should be ignored inside the warehouse.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_house_vs_warehouse.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Side-by-side comparison of House building (left) and Warehouse building (right) showing differences in interior rendering
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,16,0,4">
        Auto-Build Options
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The editor includes powerful automatic features that trigger when you draw facets
        that form a <Bold>closed polygon</Bold> (a connected loop of walls/doors with no gaps).
        All three options can be independently enabled or disabled via the
        <Bold>Auto Build Options</Bold> checkboxes in the Buildings tab:
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Auto Detect Roofs
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When enabled, the editor automatically detects closed polygons and triggers the appropriate
        interior treatment:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Houses:</Bold> Applies roof textures to the enclosed area using the intelligent
                roof texture classification system.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Warehouses:</Bold> Applies floor textures (<Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">tex287hi</Run>)
                to the interior footprint.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        A closed polygon is detected when walls (or walls + doors) form a complete connected loop
        at the same height and Y offset. Even a 1-cell gap sealed by a door counts as a closed
        polygon and will trigger the automation.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Auto Paint Roof Textures
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When enabled, the editor automatically paints textures onto detected closed polygon
        interiors. Disable this if you want to manually texture the interior later using the
        Textures tab tools.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Auto Create Walkables
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When enabled, the editor automatically creates <Bold>walkable regions</Bold> at the height
        of the drawn facets whenever a closed polygon is detected. Walkables are containers for
        <Bold>Roof Face 4 (RF4) tiles</Bold>, which define the actual surfaces players can stand
        on and move across.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        For <Bold>warehouses</Bold>, this option also auto-creates <Bold>RF4 roof tiles</Bold>
        matching the interior footprint at the walkable height. These tiles define the effective
        floor height inside the warehouse (since PAP altitude stays at 0).
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_auto_options.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Auto-Build Options checkboxes in the Buildings tab (Auto Detect Roofs, Auto Paint Roof Textures, Auto Create Walkables)
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Border Background="#2A2A3A" BorderBrush="#4A4A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#B0B0E0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>Leave all three Auto-Build options enabled when learning. They dramatically speed up building creation and handle complex tasks (walkable management, texture classification) automatically. You can always disable them later for fine-grained manual control.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Creating Your First Building
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Every facet must belong to a building. Here's how to create one:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Open the <Bold>Buildings tab</Bold> in the editor drawer on the right side of
                the screen.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click the <Bold>New Building icon</Bold> in the toolbar (looks like a house with
                a plus sign). The <Bold>Add Building</Bold> dialog appears.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Choose a building type — <Bold>House</Bold> or <Bold>Warehouse</Bold>. For your
                first building, choose <Bold>House</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click <Bold>Add Building</Bold>. The new building appears in the <Bold>Buildings
                list</Bold> on the right side of the tab.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_add_dialog.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Add Building dialog with House and Warehouse radio button options
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The building now exists as an empty container with a unique ID (e.g., <Bold>Building #1</Bold>).
        It contains no facets yet — you will add walls, doors, and other elements in the next steps.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        You can create as many buildings as needed. Each building shows up in the list and can be
        selected to view or edit its facets.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Color Coding
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Each facet type is color-coded on the map canvas for easy identification at a glance:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold Foreground="#90EE90">Green</Bold> — Walls</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold Foreground="#FFA500">Orange</Bold> — Ladders</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold Foreground="#FFFF00">Yellow</Bold> — Fences</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold Foreground="#FF6347">Red</Bold> — Cables</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold Foreground="#DA70D6">Purple</Bold> — Doors</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold Foreground="#87CEEB">Blue</Bold> — Gates</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Within each building, you can <Bold>filter</Bold> the Facets list to show only a particular
        type by clicking the associated <Bold>color pill</Bold> at the top of the Facets panel.
        For example, to see all ladders attached to a building, select the building and click the
        <Bold>orange pill</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_color_filter.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Color pill buttons at top of Facets panel (green=walls, orange=ladders, yellow=fences, red=cables, purple=doors, blue=gates)
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Next Steps
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Now that you understand building types and have created your first building container,
        you're ready to add facets. See:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Buildings: Facets</Bold> — Learn how to add walls, doors, ladders, fences,
                cables, and gates to your buildings.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Buildings: Properties</Bold> — Deep dive into facet properties like height,
